Architecture plan for the 40-issue implementation sequence

Product/source of truth
- Use the product name and tone from each GitHub issue when implementing user-facing copy. Do not introduce an unrelated agent or placeholder brand.
- Build incrementally so each issue can land independently while preserving a coherent full-stack shape.

Recommended project structure
- backend/
  - src/server.ts or src/main.ts: HTTP server bootstrap, proxy-aware trust settings, graceful shutdown.
  - src/config/: environment parsing and typed runtime configuration.
  - src/db/: PostgreSQL pool, migration runner integration, query helpers.
  - src/migrations/: ordered SQL migrations for users, events, invitations, comments, activity, and supporting indexes.
  - src/modules/auth/: password hashing, JWT/session helpers, auth middleware, registration, login, OAuth, reset, verification.
  - src/modules/users/: profile model, profile API, profile photo upload.
  - src/modules/events/: event CRUD, dashboard queries, cover upload, attachment upload/listing.
  - src/modules/invitations/: invitation sending, RSVP mutation/query APIs, reminder scheduling hooks.
  - src/modules/comments/: comment CRUD/thread APIs.
  - src/modules/activity/: append-only activity event writer and feed APIs.
  - src/lib/storage/: object storage client, signed/object key conventions, MIME and size validation.
  - src/lib/email/: platform email proxy client and email templates.
  - src/lib/http/: shared error handling, request validation, pagination, auth extraction.
  - test/: backend integration/unit tests for core flows.
- frontend/
  - src/main.tsx: app entry.
  - src/app/: router, authenticated layout, providers, theme.
  - src/api/: typed API client, session persistence, upload helpers.
  - src/auth/: register, verify email, login, OAuth callback, password reset screens.
  - src/profile/: profile view/settings and photo upload.
  - src/events/: dashboard, detail, create/edit form, attachments, attendee list.
  - src/invitations/: invitation acceptance flow and RSVP controls.
  - src/comments/: comment thread components.
  - src/activity/: activity feed components.
  - src/ui/: shared controls, form fields, empty/error/loading states, playful theme primitives.
  - src/types/: frontend-facing shared types generated from or kept in sync with backend schemas.
- shared/ (optional if the chosen stack supports it cleanly)
  - API DTO/schema definitions, validation schemas, enums, and date/status helpers used by both backend and frontend.

Issue dependency map
- #1 establishes backend/frontend scaffolding and package scripts.
- #2 supplies typed environment configuration used by all later services.
- #3 depends on #2 and enables every persistent feature.
- #4 and #5 depend on #2 and support upload/email issues.
- #6 depends on #2 and forms the API base for all backend routes.
- #7 depends on #1 and sets frontend routing/theme conventions.
- #8 depends on #3; #9 depends on #8; #10-#13 depend on #9 plus #5 for email-related flows.
- #14 depends on #7 and #10-#13 for frontend auth.
- #15-#17 depend on auth/profile foundations, with #16 also depending on #4.
- #18 depends on #3 and unlocks event features; #19 depends on #18 and #9.
- #20-#21 depend on #4 and #19.
- #22 depends on #18/#19; #23-#25 depend on #7, #14, #19, and #22.
- #26 depends on #18 and #3; #27 depends on #26, #5, and #19; #28 depends on #26 and #9.
- #29 depends on #26-#28 and #5.
- #30-#31 depend on #27-#28 plus frontend auth/event screens.
- #32 depends on #18/#26 and #3; #33-#34 depend on #32 and auth.
- #35-#36 depend on #33-#34 and established event detail UI.
- #37 should cover registration/login, event create/edit, invitation RSVP, comments, uploads where feasible.
- #38 follows feature completion and audits validation, authorization, error mapping, and edge cases.
- #39 follows stable UX and copy surfaces.
- #40 depends on build/test readiness, environment docs, migrations, and proxy-safe deployment behavior.

Key design decisions
- Use PostgreSQL as the system of record with explicit SQL migrations, foreign keys, uniqueness constraints, and created_at/updated_at timestamps.
- Keep authorization server-side. Organizer-only event mutations, upload access, invitation management, and profile edits must be enforced in backend middleware/services, not only in the UI.
- Store uploaded profile photos, event covers, and PDFs in object storage. Persist only metadata, object keys, content type, size, and ownership references in PostgreSQL.
- Use short-lived signed upload/download URLs or backend-mediated upload endpoints, with strict MIME/size validation.
- Treat email as an infrastructure boundary behind a small helper that can send verification, reset, invitation, and reminder messages through the platform proxy.
- Use JWT/session helpers behind auth middleware so later routes share one identity model. Passwords are hashed with a modern password hashing library and never logged.
- Normalize API errors into stable JSON envelopes with field-level validation details where applicable.
- Keep frontend API calls typed, centralized, and proxy-compatible. If CORS or origin checks are added, trust forwarded headers or platform-provided allowed origin.
- Prefer schema validation shared between route handlers and frontend form types when the stack makes this practical.
- Activity events should be append-only and emitted from domain actions rather than inferred only at read time.
- Add focused tests as features land, then broaden to end-to-end coverage for the core flows near #37.
